article.description: Maria Stepanova scored 12 of her 18 points in the second half to lead the host Phoenix Mercury to a 70-64 win Wednesday night and send the Minnesota Lynx to their fifth straight loss.
article.headline: Phoenix inching closer to a playoff spot
article.linkText: Stepanova, Mercury hand Lynx fifth straight loss
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury have overcome a 3-11 start to
put themselves back in WNBA playoff contention.

Maria Stepanova scored 12 of her season-high 18 points in the
second half and Phoenix beat Minnesota 70-64 on Wednesday night,
the Lynx's fifth straight loss.

Penny Taylor had 15 points, seven rebounds and four assists for
the Mercury (11-13), who moved a half-game ahead of the Lynx
(11-14) and a half-game behind Los Angeles for the fourth and final
playoff spot in the Western Conference.

"We didn't start the game our way, like we wanted," Phoenix's
Kamila Vodichkova said. "I think it energized us for the second
half. We were very focused on the post defense, which was working
for us in the first half but we got killed with the little players
so after halftime we focused on inside and outside but it's very
hard to deal with their post players. It's a battle."

The Lynx were 9-for-13 from the field over the final 8 minutes
of the first half and scored the last eight points of the period to
take a 38-29 lead. But Phoenix had a 16-5 run in the second half to
take a 64-55 lead with 2:21 left.

Minnesota was 10-of-33 from the field in the second half.

"I've very disappointed that in crunch time we couldn't get
defensive stops when we needed to and come away with the ball,"
Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said.

Minnesota has lost six of seven. It was the second loss for the
Lynx since trading leading scorer Katie Smith, the first
professional women's player to score 5,000 points.

Svetlana Abrosimova led the Lynx with 19 points and Kristi
Harrower and Chandi Jones each added 11. Nicole Ohlde, Minnesota's
second-leading scorer, was held to 2-of-7 shooting from the field
for four points, seven under her average.

"They came out a lot stronger, like they were going to win, and
we kind of followed their lead instead of becoming more aggressive
in the second half," Abrosimova said.

Vodichkova had 14 points and eight rebounds for Phoenix, which
has won eight of 10.

"It wasn't pretty but it was a 'W," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf
said. "Minnesota outplayed us in the first half, there's no
question our perimeter defense was really poor."

It was the Mercury's fourth win in 16 tries when trailing at
halftime.

"The second half we tried to contain them and get really good
ball pressure so we could keep them out of the paint," Taylor
said. "We had to be a lot more aggressive, not so much shooting
the ball but making the extra pass and getting a good shot."

Phoenix played the last 16 minutes without Anna DeForge, who
averages 13.4 points. She sprained her right knee and was to be
evaluated Thursday.
